{{Infobox venue | name = Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz | image = Das Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz 04.jpg | image_upright = 1.2 | caption = Gärtnerplatztheater from the square, in 2018 | image_map = | map_caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_caption= <!--Location within Munich --> | address = | city = [[Munich]], [[Bavaria]] | country = Germany | designation = | coordinates = {{coord|48|07|52|N|11|34|32|E|display=inline,title}} | architect = Franz Michael Reiffenstuel | owner = State of Bavaria | tenant = | operator = | capacity = | type = Theatre | opened = {{start date|1865|11|04|df=y}} | reopened = {{hlist | 1948 | 2016 }} | yearsactive = | rebuilt = | closed = | demolished = | othernames = | production = | currentuse = | publictransit = | website = {{url|http://www.staatstheater-am-gaertnerplatz.de/}} }} The '''Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz''' (''State Theatre at Gärtnerplatz''), commonly called the '''Gärtnerplatztheater''', is an [[opera house]] and [[opera]] company in [[Munich]]. (The "Gärtnerplatz" is an urban square in the borough [[Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt]].) Designed by Michael Reiffenstuel, it opened on 4 November 1865 as the city's second major theatre after the [[National Theatre Munich|National Theatre]].
At times exclusively concerned with [[operetta]], in recent years there have also been productions of opera, musicals and ballet. The scope of activities is similar to that of the [[Komische Oper]] in Berlin and the [[English National Opera]] in London.
One of the most active theatres in [[Germany]], its season lasts from September to July and comprises more than 200 performances. The current [[intendant]] is Josef Ernst Köpplinger.
== History == In 1863, a committee for the founding of a ''Volkstheater'' (people's theatre) formed. [[Ludwig II of Bavaria]] authorized a new building in the borough Isarvorstadt on 10 May 1864. It was designed by [[Franz Michael Reiffenstuel]],<ref>[http://www.nordostkultur-muenchen.de/biographien/reiffenstruel.htm Die Reiffenstuels]</ref> who modelled it after the [[Nationaltheater München|Nationaltheater]] in [[Classicist architecture|classicist style]].{{sfn|Munich|2018}}{{sfn|Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz|1965|p=43}} The groundbreaking was on 25 August 1864, and the ''Richtfest'' was celebrated on 27 May 1865.{{sfn|Busse|1924|pp=13–15}} The house was opened on 4 November 1865,{{sfn|Hußlein|2015}} with [[Duke Maximilian Joseph in Bavaria]] representing the king. The opening performance was a Prologue followed by an allegorical festive play (''Festspiel'') by Hermann Schmid, ''Was wir wollen'' (What we want), with music by {{ill|Georg Kremplsetzer|de}}“.{{sfn|Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz|1965|p=12}}
The house, intended to show a different repertory than the court theatre,{{sfn|Hußlein|2015}} met with financial problems, under frequently changing directors. It had to be sold in March 1870, went first to the former director Friedrich Engelken, shortly thereafter to the architect and a partner, who bought it for the king, who acquired it officially in May 1870. It was reopened on 1 October 1870, directed by [[Hermann von Schmid]].{{sfn|Busse|1924|pp=19–21}} In 1873, Ludwig II granted it the name "Königliches Theater am Gärtnerplatz" (Royal theatre at the Gärtnerplatz).{{sfn|Munich|2018}} From 1877, {{ill|Karl von Perfall|de}} directed the house and also the Hoftheater. The 1878/79 season was especially splendid but resulted in a large deficit. Perfall therefore focused on the Hoftheater, and was succeeded by Georg Lang. The theatre dropped the royal emblem and was called "Theater am Gärtnerplatz".{{sfn|Busse|1924|pp=29–30}}
In 1913, the house was rebuilt by {{ill|Eugen Drollinger|de}}, who designed a new approach by the audience to the tiers, and installed more loges.{{sfn|Busse|1924|pp=325}} During World War I, several charity performances were given for the ''Kriegsfonds'' and social organisations.{{sfn|Busse|1924|p=44}} In 1923, the house was acquired by the {{ill|Wittelsbacher Ausgleichsfonds|de}}.
When the theatre was built, the focus was on [[operetta]], then a new genre.{{sfn|Hußlein|2015}} [[Singspiel]]e, light operas with spoken dialogue in German, were also performed. When the house opened as a royal theatre, [[Jacques Offenbach]]'s ''Salon Pitzelberger'' was played, titled ''Eine musikalische Soirée in der Vorstadt'' (A musical soiree in the suburb). Some operettas received their world premiere, including [[Carl Zeller]]'s ''Die Fornarina'' on 18 October 1979, starring {{ill|Amalie Schönchen|de}}, Agnes Lang-Ratthey, {{ill|Franz Josef Brakl|de}}} and Max Hofpauer. At the end of 1892, a ''Völkerschau'' (People's Show), ''Die Amazonen von Dahomey'', appeared with people from Africa for several weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=So rassistisch waren die Völkerschauen in München|periodical=|publisher=www.sueddeutsche.de|url=http://www.sueddeutsche.de/muenchen/grosser-andrang-abschied-von-cula-1.3746431|accessdate=2017-11-13|last=Marco Wedig|date=2017-11-12|language=German}}</ref>
[[File:Gärtnerplatzthea.jpg|thumb|The theatre c. 1900]] From 1899, the theatre played mainly operettas and was regarded as one of the leading houses for the genre in Germany.{{sfn|Busse|1924|pp=32}} [[Fanny zu Reventlow]] was engaged for a short time. [[Magda Schneider]] appeared at the end of the 1920s, complaining that she had to perform up to 48 times a month for a laughable salary ("für eine lächerliche Gage bis zu achtundvierzig mal im Monat auf der Bühne").<ref>Jürgs 2000, p. 18.</ref> Some ''Possen'' and ''Volksstücke'' were presented until the 1930s, when the [[Nazi regime]] banned performances by Jewish writers, librettists and composers, and demanded that the theatre serve as a venue exclusively for operettas, as the operetta was an excellent means of familiarizing the ordinary citizen with the theater arts ("ausschließlich zur Aufführungsstätte von Operetten, weil… die Operette ein sehr wesentliches Mittel ist, um den Volksgenossen an die Theaterkunst heranzuführen").<ref>Aktionskreis Gärtnerplatztheater, 1979, p. 22.</ref>
[[File:Giita.jpg|thumb|Program of ''Gitta'', 1942, with Elisabeth Biebl in the title role]] In April 1937, the state of Bavaria became owner of the theatre.{{sfn|Munich|2018}} Plans to replace it with a new building were not realised, but the house was restored. The reopening of the only state operetta house in Germany on 20 November 1937 presented ''[[Die Fledermaus]]'' by Johann Strauss, with [[Adolf Hitler]] in the audience. From 1938, Fritz Fischer was the [[intendant]] and [[Peter Kreuder]] was the music director. Fischer showed a new style, influenced by Berlin [[revue]]s and filmed operettas, with mass scenes, opulent staging and fast action.<ref>''Bayerisches Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz.'' 1965, p. 26 f.</ref> ''Gitta. Eine Fahrt ins Blaue'', a ''Lustspieloperette'' composed by Bernhard Stimmler and Carl Michalski, premiered on 18 May 1942, presenting the new style. ''[[The Merry Widow|Die lustige Witwe]]'' was also played, the declared favourite operetta of Hitler, who attended the theatre frequently.{{sfn|Jungblut|2017}}
On 21 April 1945, the theatre was badly damaged by the last bombing of Munich.{{sfn|Munich|2018}} Shortly after the war, performances were held at a Schornstraße location, and the restored theatre was reopened{{sfn|Munich|2018}} on 19 June 1948, playing ''[[Eine Nacht in Venedig]]'' by Johann Strauss. The Gärtnerplatztheater was able to secure [[Gustaf Gründgens]] to stage, as a guest, Offenbach's ''[[Les brigands|Die Banditen]]'' (The Bandits), first performed on 6 July 1949, with Gründgens playing a major role ("mit intellektuell-komödantischer Bravour").{{sfn|Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz|1965|p=30}} The theatre played mainly popular works, including Millöcker's ''[[Der Bettelstudent]]'', Abraham's ''[[Viktoria und ihr Husar]]'', Kálmán's ''[[Die Csárdásfürstin]]'' with [[Sári Barabás]] in the title role, and ''[[Gräfin Mariza]]'', Zeller's ''[[Der Vogelhändler]]'', and Lehár's ''[[Das Land des Lächelns]]'', with {{ill|Elisabeth Biebl|de|Elisabeth Biebl (Schauspielerin)|lt=Elisabeth Biebl}} as Mi and {{ill|Harry Friedauer|de}} as Gustl. The world premiere of Burkhard's ''[[Das Feuerwerk]]'', staged by [[Erik Charell]] on 16 May 1950, was noticed well beyond Munich.
From 1952 to 1955, {{ill|Rudolf Hartmann|de|Rudolf Hartmann (Regisseur)}}, who also directed the [[Bayerische Staatsoper]], led the theatre.{{sfn|Munich|2018}} He initiated the performance of operas, but with the ensemble of the State Opera.{{sfn|Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz|1965|p=32}} From 1955, the theatre was again independent and officially named Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz,{{sfn|Munich|2018}} led by Willy Duvoisin (1955 to 1958), [[Arno Assmann]] (1959 to 1964), {{ill|Kurt Pscherer|de}} (1964 to 1983), {{ill|Hellmuth Matiasek|de}} (1983 to 1996), {{ill|Klaus Schultz|de}} (1996 to 2007), {{ill|Ulrich Peters (director)|de|Ulrich Peters|lt=Ulrich Peters}} (2007 to 2012) and {{ill|Josef Ernst Köpplinger|de}} (since 2012).{{sfn|Munich|2018}} The chief conductor is [[Anthony Bramall]] (since 2017), and the director of dance is Karl Alfred Schreiner (since 2012).{{sfn|Munich|2018}}
[[File:München Staatstheater am Gärtnerplatz innen.jpg|thumb|Interior in 2008]] In 1955, the first musical was performed at the Gärtnerplatz, the German premiere of Harold Rome's ''[[Fanny (musical)|Fanny]]'',{{sfn|Jansen|2012|pp=21–22}}{{sfn|Siedhoff|1990}} with {{ill|Christine Görner|de}} and [[Trude Hesterberg]] in leading roles. It was followed a year later by Cole Porter's ''[[Kiss Me, Kate (musical)|Kiss Me, Kate]]'' with [[Johannes Heesters]].{{sfn|Siedhoff|1990}} Loewe's ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' was performed in 1984, staged by [[August Everding]] and with [[Cornelia Froboess]] as Eliza Doolittle.{{sfn|VDOper|2018}} In 1957, the theatre showed the first performance in Munich of Stravinsky's opera ''[[The Rake's Progress]]''.{{sfn|Ganz München|2018}} World premieres of operas included {{ill|Paul Engel (composer)|de|Paul Engel|lt=Paul Engel}}'s ''Daniel'' in 1994,{{sfn|Kutsch|Riemens|2004|p=1577}}, [[Avet Terterian]]'s ''Das Beben'' in 2003,{{sfn|Kuhn|2003}} and {{ill|Wilfried Hiller|de}} ''Der Flaschengeist'' in 2014,{{sfn|Braunmüller|2014}} among others.<!-- and Johann Maria Staud. -->
The theatre was closed in 2012 for extensive restoration.{{sfn|Munich|2018}}{{sfn|Jungblut|2017}} It was reopened on 15 October 2017 with a gala performance followed by a new production of ''Die lustige Witwe'' on 19 October.{{sfn|Jungblut|2017}}{{sfn|Tholl|2017}}
